question:
Of the eight studentsâ€”George, Helen, Irving, Kyle, Lenore, Nina, Olivia, and Robertâ€”in a seminar, exactly six will give individual oral reports during three consecutive daysâ€”Monday, Tuesday, and Wednesday. Exactly two reports will be given each dayâ€”one in the morning and one in the afternoonâ€”according to the following conditions: Tuesday is the only day on which George can give a report. Neither Olivia nor Robert can give an afternoon report. If Nina gives a report, then on the next day Helen and Irving must both give reports, unless Nina's report is given on Wednesday.

Which one of the following could be the schedule of the students' reports?
A) Mon. morning: Helen; Mon. afternoon: Robert Tues. morning: Olivia; Tues. afternoon: Irving Wed. morning: Lenore; Wed. afternoon: Kyle
B) Mon. morning: Irving; Mon. afternoon: Olivia Tues. morning: Helen; Tues. afternoon: Kyle Wed. morning: Nina; Wed. afternoon: Lenore
C) Mon. morning: Lenore; Mon. afternoon: Helen Tues. morning: George; Tues. afternoon: Kyle Wed. morning: Robert; Wed. afternoon: Irving
D) Mon. morning: Nina; Mon. afternoon: Helen Tues. morning: Robert; Tues. afternoon: Irving Wed. morning: Olivia; Wed. afternoon: Lenore
E) Mon. morning: Olivia; Mon. afternoon: Nina Tues. morning: Irving; Tues. afternoon: Helen Wed. morning: Kyle; Wed. afternoon: George

question:
Of the eight studentsâ€”George, Helen, Irving, Kyle, Lenore, Nina, Olivia, and Robertâ€”in a seminar, exactly six will give individual oral reports during three consecutive daysâ€”Monday, Tuesday, and Wednesday. Exactly two reports will be given each dayâ€”one in the morning and one in the afternoonâ€”according to the following conditions: Tuesday is the only day on which George can give a report. Neither Olivia nor Robert can give an afternoon report. If Nina gives a report, then on the next day Helen and Irving must both give reports, unless Nina's report is given on Wednesday.

If George, Nina, and Robert give reports and they do so on different days from one another, which one of the following could be true?
A) Helen gives a report on Wednesday.
B) Nina gives a report on Monday.
C) Nina gives a report on Tuesday.
D) Olivia gives a report on Monday.
E) Robert gives a report on Wednesday.

question:
The organizer of a reading club will select at least five and at most six works from a group of nine works. The group consists of three French novels, three Russian novels, two French plays, and one Russian play. The organizer's selection of works must conform to the following requirements: No more than four French works are selected. At least three but no more than four novels are selected. At least as many French novels as Russian novels are selected. If both French plays are selected, then the Russian play is not selected.

Which one of the following could be the organizer's selection of works?
A) one French novel, two Russian novels, one French play, one Russian play
B) two French novels, one Russian novel, two French plays, one Russian play
C) two French novels, two Russian novels, two French plays
D) three French novels, one Russian novel, two French plays
E) three French novels, two Russian novels, one Russian play

question:
The organizer of a reading club will select at least five and at most six works from a group of nine works. The group consists of three French novels, three Russian novels, two French plays, and one Russian play. The organizer's selection of works must conform to the following requirements: No more than four French works are selected. At least three but no more than four novels are selected. At least as many French novels as Russian novels are selected. If both French plays are selected, then the Russian play is not selected.

Which one of the following could be true about the organizer's selection of works?
A) No Russian novels are selected.
B) Exactly one French novel is selected.
C) All three plays are selected.
D) All three Russian novels are selected.
E) All five French works are selected.

question:
The organizer of a reading club will select at least five and at most six works from a group of nine works. The group consists of three French novels, three Russian novels, two French plays, and one Russian play. The organizer's selection of works must conform to the following requirements: No more than four French works are selected. At least three but no more than four novels are selected. At least as many French novels as Russian novels are selected. If both French plays are selected, then the Russian play is not selected.

If the works selected include three French novels, which one of the following could be a complete and accurate list of the remaining works selected?
A) one Russian novel
B) two French plays
C) one Russian novel, one Russian play
D) one Russian novel, two French plays
E) two Russian novels, one French play

question:
The organizer of a reading club will select at least five and at most six works from a group of nine works. The group consists of three French novels, three Russian novels, two French plays, and one Russian play. The organizer's selection of works must conform to the following requirements: No more than four French works are selected. At least three but no more than four novels are selected. At least as many French novels as Russian novels are selected. If both French plays are selected, then the Russian play is not selected.

The organizer must at least select
A) one French novel and one French play
B) one French novel and one Russian play
C) one Russian novel and one French play
D) two French novels
E) two Russian novels
chain_of_thought: We are given a set of rules for selecting books to be placed on a shelf. We need to determine the minimum number of books that must be selected according to these rules. The rules are: 1. H is somewhere to the left of J. 2. K is immediately to the right of H. 3. G is not at either end of the row. 4. There are at least three but no more than four novels. 5. There are at least as many French novels as Russian novels. 6. If both French plays are selected, then the Russian play is not selected. Let's analyze the rules step by step: 1. **H is somewhere to the left of J**: - This means H must be before J in the order. 2. **K is immediately to the right of H**: - This means H must be followed by K. 3. **G is not at either end of the row**: - This means G cannot be in the first or last position. 4. **There are at least three but no more than four novels**: - This means the number of novels must be 3 or 4. 5. **There are at least as many French novels as Russian novels**: - This means the number of French novels must be at least as many as the number of Russian novels. 6. **If both French plays are selected, then the Russian play is not selected**: - This means if both F1 and F2 are selected, F3 cannot be selected. Let's consider the minimum number of books that can be selected while satisfying all these rules. ### Case 1: Three Novels If we have three novels, they can be either F1, F2, F3 or F1, F2, R1 or F1, R1, F3 or F1, R1, R2 or F2, F3 or F2, R1 or R1, F3 or R1, R2. #### Subcase 1.1: F1, F2, F3 - This satisfies rule 1 and rule 2 (H=F1, J(F2), K(F3)). - This does not satisfy rule 5 because there are more French novels than Russian novels. #### Subcase 1.2: F1, F2, R1 - This satisfies rule 1 and rule 2 (H=F1, J(F2), K(F3)). - This does not satisfy rule 6 because both French plays are selected. #### Subcase 1.3: F1, F3, F2 - This does not satisfy rule 2. #### Subcase 1.4: F1, F3, R1 - This does not satisfy rule 2. #### Subcase 1.5: F1, R1, F3 - This does not satisfy rule 2. #### Subcase 1.6: F1, R1, R2 - This does not satisfy rule 2. #### Subcase 1.7: F2, F3, F1 - This does not satisfy rule 2. #### Subcase 1.8: F2, F3, R1 - This does not satisfy rule 2. #### Subcase 1.9: F2, R1, F3 - This does not satisfy rule 2. #### Subcase 1.10: F2, R1, R2 - This does not satisfy rule 2. #### Subcase 1.11: F3, F1, F2 - This does not satisfy rule 2. #### Subcase 1.12: F3, F1, R1 - This does not satisfy rule 2. #### Subcase 1.13: F3, R1, F2 - This does not satisfy rule 2. #### Subcase 1.14: F3, R1, R2 - This does not satisfy rule 2. Since none of the subcases for three novels satisfy all the rules, we need to consider four novels. ### Case 2: Four Novels If we have four novels, they can be either F1, F2, F3, F4 or F1, F2, F3, R1 or F1, F2, R1, F4 or F1, R1, F2, F4 or F1, R1, R2, F4 or F2, F3, F4 or F2, F3, R2 or F2, R2, F4 or F1, F2, R1, F4 or F1, R1, R2. #### Subcase 2.1: F1, F2, F3, F4 - This satisfies all rules. - This is a valid selection. Since we have found a valid selection with four novels that satisfies all rules, the minimum number of books that must be selected is 4. question:
The organizer of a reading club will select at least five and at most six works from a group of nine works. The group consists of three French novels, three Russian novels, two French plays, and one Russian play. The organizer's selection of works must conform to the following requirements: No more than four French works are selected. At least three but no more than four novels are selected. At least as many French novels as Russian novels are selected. If both French plays are selected, then the Russian play is not selected.

Any one of the following could be true about the organizer's selections of works EXCEPT:
A) No Russian novels and exactly one play are selected.
B) Exactly one Russian novel and both French plays are selected.
C) Exactly two French novels and the Russian play are selected.
D) Exactly two French novels and exactly two plays are selected.
E) Exactly two Russian novels and exactly one play are selected.

question:
On each of exactly seven consecutive days (day 1 though day 7), a pet shop features exactly one of three breeds of kittenâ€”Himalayan, Manx, Siameseâ€”and exactly one of three breeds of puppyâ€”Greyhound, Newfoundland, Rottweiler. The following conditions must apply: Greyhounds are featured on day 1. No breed is featured on any two consecutive days. Any breed featured on day 1 is not featured on day 7. Himalayans are featured on exactly three days, but not on day 1. Rottweilers are not featured on day 7, nor on any day that features Himalayans.

Which one of the following could be true?
A) There are exactly four breeds that are each featured on three days.
B) Greyhounds are featured on every day that Himalayans are.
C) Himalayans are featured on every day that Greyhounds are.
D) Himalayans are featured on every day that Rottweilers are not.
E) Rottweilers are featured on every day that Himalayans are not.

question:
On each of exactly seven consecutive days (day 1 though day 7), a pet shop features exactly one of three breeds of kittenâ€”Himalayan, Manx, Siameseâ€”and exactly one of three breeds of puppyâ€”Greyhound, Newfoundland, Rottweiler. The following conditions must apply: Greyhounds are featured on day 1. No breed is featured on any two consecutive days. Any breed featured on day 1 is not featured on day 7. Himalayans are featured on exactly three days, but not on day 1. Rottweilers are not featured on day 7, nor on any day that features Himalayans.

If Himalayans are not featured on day 7, which one of the following could be true?
A) Greyhounds are featured on days 3 and 5.
B) Newfoundlands are featured on day 3.
C) Rottweilers are featured on day 6.
D) Rottweilers are featured only on day 3.
E) Rottweilers are featured on exactly three days.

question:
A panel of five scientists will be formed. The panelists will be selected from among three botanistsâ€”F, G, and Hâ€”three chemistsâ€”K, L, and Mâ€”and three zoologistsâ€”P, Q, and R. Selection is governed by the following conditions: The panel must include at least one scientist of each of the three types. If more than one botanist is selected, then at most one zoologist is selected. F and K cannot both be selected. K and M cannot both be selected. If M is selected, both P and R must be selected.

If M is the only chemist selected for the panel, which one of the following must be true?
A) F and G are both selected.
B) G and H are both selected.
C) H and P are both selected.
D) F, G, and H are all selected.
E) P, Q, and R are all selected.

B) H
C) K
D) M

question:
A loading dock consists of exactly six bays numbered 1 through 6 consecutively from one side of the dock to the other. Each bay is holding a different one of exactly six types of cargoâ€”fuel, grain, livestock, machinery, produce, or textiles. The following apply: The bay holding grain has a higher number than the bay holding livestock. The bay holding livestock has a higher number than the bay holding textiles. The bay holding produce has a higher number than the bay holding fuel. The bay holding textiles is next to the bay holding produce.

Which one of the following CANNOT be the type of cargo held in bay 4?
A) grain
B) livestock
C) machinery
D) produce
E) textiles

question:
A loading dock consists of exactly six bays numbered 1 through 6 consecutively from one side of the dock to the other. Each bay is holding a different one of exactly six types of cargoâ€”fuel, grain, livestock, machinery, produce, or textiles. The following apply: The bay holding grain has a higher number than the bay holding livestock. The bay holding livestock has a higher number than the bay holding textiles. The bay holding produce has a higher number than the bay holding fuel. The bay holding textiles is next to the bay holding produce.

If there is exactly one bay between the bay holding machinery and the bay holding grain, then for exactly how many of the six bays is the type of cargo that bay is holding completely determined?
A) two
B) three
C) four
D) five
E) six

C) bay 3
D) bay 5
E) bay 6

Each bay is holding a different one of exactly six types of cargoâ€”fuel, grain, livestock, machinery, produce, or textiles. The following apply: The bay holding grain has a higher number than the bay holding livestock. The bay holding livestock has a higher number than the bay holding textiles. The bay holding produce has a higher number than the bay holding fuel. The bay holding textiles is next to the bay holding produce.

Which one of the following must be false?
A) The bay holding fuel is next to the bay holding machinery.
B) The bay holding grain is next to the bay holding machinery.
C) The bay holding livestock is next to the bay holding fuel.
D) The bay holding produce is next to the bay holding livestock.
E) The bay holding textiles is next to the bay holding fuel.

question:
A bakery makes exactly three kinds of cookieâ€”oatmeal, peanut butter, and sugar. Exactly three batches of each kind of cookie are made each week (Monday through Friday) and each batch is made, from start to finish, on a single day. The following conditions apply: No two batches of the same kind of cookie are made on the same day. At least one batch of cookies is made on Monday. The second batch of oatmeal cookies is made on the same day as the first batch of peanut butter cookies. The second batch of sugar cookies is made on Thursday.

Which one of the following could be a complete and accurate list of the days on which the batches of each kind of cookie are made?
A) oatmeal: Monday, Wednesday, Thursday peanut butter: Wednesday, Thursday, Friday sugar: Monday, Thursday, Friday
B) oatmeal: Monday, Tuesday, Thursday peanut butter: Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday sugar: Monday, Wednesday, Thursday
C) oatmeal: Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday peanut butter: Wednesday, Thursday, Friday sugar: Tuesday, Thursday, Friday
D) oatmeal: Monday, Tuesday, Thursday peanut butter: Monday, Wednesday, Thursday sugar: Monday, Thursday, Friday
E) oatmeal: Monday, Thursday, Friday peanut butter: Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday sugar: Monday, Thursday, Friday

question:
A bakery makes exactly three kinds of cookieâ€”oatmeal, peanut butter, and sugar. Exactly three batches of each kind of cookie are made each week (Monday through Friday) and each batch is made, from start to finish, on a single day. The following conditions apply: No two batches of the same kind of cookie are made on the same day. At least one batch of cookies is made on Monday. The second batch of oatmeal cookies is made on the same day as the first batch of peanut butter cookies. The second batch of sugar cookies is made on Thursday.

How many of the days, Monday through Friday, are such that at most two batches of cookies could be made on that day?
A) one
B) two
C) three
D) four
E) five

question:
A bakery makes exactly three kinds of cookieâ€”oatmeal, peanut butter, and sugar. Exactly three batches of each kind of cookie are made each week (Monday through Friday) and each batch is made, from start to finish, on a single day. The following conditions apply: No two batches of the same kind of cookie are made on the same day. At least one batch of cookies is made on Monday. The second batch of oatmeal cookies is made on the same day as the first batch of peanut butter cookies. The second batch of sugar cookies is made on Thursday.

If the first batch of peanut butter cookies is made on Tuesday, then each of the following could be true EXCEPT:
A) Two different kinds of cookie have their first batch made on Monday.
B) Two different kinds of cookie have their first batch made on Tuesday.
C) Two different kinds of cookie have their second batch made on Wednesday.
D) Two different kinds of cookie have their second batch made on Thursday.
E) Two different kinds of cookie have their third batch made on Friday.
chain_of_thought:
To determine the correct answer for the given problem, we need to analyze the conditions and constraints provided. Let's break it down step by step.

1. **Identify the days and cookies:**
   - There are three kinds of cookies: oatmeal (O), peanut butter (P), and sugar (S).
   - There are five days: Monday (M), Tuesday (T), Wednesday (W), Thursday (Th), and Friday (F).
   - Each kind of cookie has exactly three batches, one each day.

2. **Given conditions:**
   - No two batches of the same kind of cookie are made on the same day.
   - At least one batch of cookies is made on Monday.
   - The second batch of oatmeal cookies is made on the same day as the first batch of peanut butter cookies.
   - The second batch of sugar cookies is made on Thursday.

3. **Assign the second batches:**
   - The second batch of oatmeal cookies is made on the same day as the first batch of peanut butter cookies. Let's denote this day as \(X\).
   - The second batch of sugar cookies is made on Thursday.

   Therefore, we have:
   - \( \text{Second batch of oatmeal cookies} = X \)
   - \( \text{First batch of peanut butter cookies} = X \)
   - \( \text{Second batch of sugar cookies} = \text{Thursday} \)

4. **Determine the possible days for the first batches:**
   - Since \(X\) cannot be Monday (because at least one batch is made on Monday and \(X\) is the same day as the first batch of peanut butter cookies), \(X\) must be Tuesday, Wednesday, or Friday.
   - The second batch of oatmeal cookies must also be on Tuesday, Wednesday, or Friday.

5. **Analyze each option:**
   - **Option A: Two different kinds of cookie have their first batch made on Monday.**
     - This is possible if the first batch of oatmeal cookies is on Monday, but since \(X\) cannot be Monday, this is not possible.

   - **Option B: Two different kinds of cookie have their first batch made on Tuesday.**
     - This is possible if \(X\) is Tuesday.

   - **Option C: Two different kinds of cookie have their second batch made on Wednesday.**
     - This is possible if \(X\) is Wednesday.

   - **Option D: Two different kinds of cookie have their second batch made on Thursday.**
     - This is possible if \(X\) is not Thursday (which it is not since the second batch of sugar cookies is on Thursday).

   - **Option E: Two different kinds of cookie have their third batch made on Friday.**
     - This is possible if \(X\) is not Friday (which it is not since the second batch of oatmeal cookies is on \(X\) and \(X\) cannot be Friday).

6. **Conclusion:**
   - The only option that cannot be true is Option A.

Therefore, the answer is \(\boxed{A}\).

question:
A bakery makes exactly three kinds of cookieâ€”oatmeal, peanut butter, and sugar. Exactly three batches of each kind of cookie are made each week (Monday through Friday) and each batch is made, from start to finish, on a single day. The following conditions apply: No two batches of the same kind of cookie are made on the same day. At least one batch of cookies is made on Monday. The second batch of oatmeal cookies is made on the same day as the first batch of peanut butter cookies. The second batch of sugar cookies is made on Thursday.

If the number of batches made on Friday is exactly one, then which one of the following could be true?
A) The first batch of sugar cookies is made on Monday.
B) The first batch of oatmeal cookies is made on Tuesday.
C) The third batch of oatmeal cookies is made on Friday.
D) The first batch of peanut butter cookies is made on Wednesday.
E) The second batch of peanut butter cookies is made on Tuesday.
chain_of_thought:
To solve this problem, we need to carefully analyze the given conditions and determine the possible schedule for the batches of cookies. Let's break it down step by step.

1. **Identify the days and cookies:**
   - Days: Monday (M), Tuesday (T), Wednesday (W), Thursday (Th), Friday (F)
   - Cookies: Oatmeal (O), Peanut Butter (P), Sugar (S)
   - Conditions:
     - No two batches of the same kind of cookie are made on the same day.
     - At least one batch of cookies is made on Monday.
     - The second batch of oatmeal cookies is made on the same day as the first batch of peanut butter cookies.
     - The second batch of sugar cookies is made on Thursday.
     - The number of batches made on Friday is exactly one.

2. **Determine the position of the second batch of sugar cookies:**
   - The second batch of sugar cookies is made on Thursday (Th).

3. **Determine the position of the second batch of oatmeal cookies and the first batch of peanut butter cookies:**
   - The second batch of oatmeal cookies is made on the same day as the first batch of peanut butter cookies. Since the second batch of sugar cookies is on Thursday, the second batch of oatmeal cookies and the first batch of peanut butter cookies cannot be on Thursday. They must be on one of the other four days (M, T, W, F).

4. **Consider the number of batches made on Friday:**
   - The number of batches made on Friday is exactly one. This means one of the cookies (O, P, S) must be made on Friday.

5. **Analyze the possible positions for the batches:**
   - Since the second batch of sugar cookies is on Thursday, the remaining days for the other batches are Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, and Friday.
   - The second batch of oatmeal cookies and the first batch of peanut butter cookies must be on one of these days, and they must be on the same day.
   - The second batch of oatmeal cookies and the first batch of peanut butter cookies cannot be on Thursday or Friday because the second batch of sugar cookies is on Thursday and the number of batches made on Friday is one.

6. **Check each option to see which one fits all conditions:**

   **Option A: The first batch of sugar cookies is made on Monday.**
   - If the first batch of sugar cookies is made on Monday, the second batch of sugar cookies is on Thursday.
   - The second batch of oatmeal cookies and the first batch of peanut butter cookies must be on the same day, which cannot be Monday because we already have a batch of sugar cookies on Monday.
   - Therefore, Option A is not possible.

   **Option B: The first batch of oatmeal cookies is made on Tuesday.**
   - If the first batch of oatmeal cookies is made on Tuesday, the second batch of oatmeal cookies is also on Tuesday.
   - The second batch of sugar cookies is on Thursday.
   - The first batch of peanut butter cookies must be on Wednesday (since it cannot be on Tuesday or Thursday).
   - The second batch of oatmeal cookies is on Tuesday, and the second batch of sugar cookies is on Thursday.
   - The remaining day, Friday, must be used for the second batch of peanut butter cookies.
   - This configuration satisfies all conditions.
   - Therefore, Option B is possible.

   **Option C: The third batch of oatmeal cookies is made on Friday.**
   - If the third batch of oatmeal cookies is made on Friday, the second batch of oatmeal cookies cannot be on Friday.
   - The second batch of sugar cookies is on Thursday.
   - The second batch of oatmeal cookies and the first batch of peanut butter cookies must be on the same day, which cannot be Friday because we already have a batch of oatmeal cookies on Friday.
   - Therefore, Option C is not possible.

   **Option D: The first batch of peanut butter cookies is made on Wednesday.**
   - If the first batch of peanut butter cookies is made on Wednesday, the second batch of peanut butter cookies must also be on Wednesday.
   - The second batch of sugar cookies is on Thursday.
   - The second batch of oatmeal cookies and the first batch of peanut butter cookies must be on the same day, which cannot be Wednesday because we already have a batch of peanut butter cookies on Wednesday.
   - Therefore, Option D is not possible.

   **Option E: The second batch of peanut butter cookies is made on Tuesday.**
   - If the second batch of peanut butter cookies is made on Tuesday, the first batch of peanut butter cookies must also be on Tuesday.
   - The second batch of sugar cookies is on Thursday.
   - The second batch of oatmeal cookies and the first batch of peanut butter cookies must be on the same day, which cannot be Tuesday because we already have a batch of peanut butter cookies on Tuesday.
   - Therefore, Option E is not possible.

question:
An administrator must assign parking spaces to six new employees: Robertson, Souza, Togowa, Vaughn, Xu, and Young. Each of the six employees must be assigned one of the following parking spaces: #1, #2, #3, #4, #5, or #6. No two employees can be assigned the same parking space. The following rules govern the assignment of parking spaces: Young must be assigned a higher-numbered parking space than Togowa. Xu must be assigned a higher-numbered parking space than Souza. Robertson must be assigned a higher-numbered parking space than Young. Robertson must be assigned parking space #1, #2, #3, or #4.

Which one of the following could be the assignment of parking spaces to the new employees?
A) #1: Young; #2: Souza; #3: Vaughn; #4: Robertson; #5: Togowa; #6: Xu
B) #1: Vaughn; #2: Togowa; #3: Young; #4: Souza; #5: Robertson; #6: Xu
C) #1: Togowa; #2: Young; #3: Xu; #4: Robertson; #5: Souza; #6: Vaughn
D) #1: Togowa; #2: Robertson; #3: Young; #4: Souza; #5: Vaughn; #6: Xu
E) #1: Souza; #2: Togowa; #3: Young; #4: Robertson; #5: Xu; #6: Vaughn

question:
An administrator must assign parking spaces to six new employees: Robertson, Souza, Togowa, Vaughn, Xu, and Young. Each of the six employees must be assigned one of the following parking spaces: #1, #2, #3, #4, #5, or #6. No two employees can be assigned the same parking space. The following rules govern the assignment of parking spaces: Young must be assigned a higher-numbered parking space than Togowa. Xu must be assigned a higher-numbered parking space than Souza. Robertson must be assigned a higher-numbered parking space than Young. Robertson must be assigned parking space #1, #2, #3, or #4.

For how many of the six new employees is the assignment of a parking space limited to one of only two possible spaces?
A) none
B) two
C) three
D) four
E) five

question:
A government needs to assign new ambassadors to Venezuela, Yemen, and Zambia. The candidates for these ambassadorships are Jaramillo, Kayne, Landon, Novetzke, and Ong. One ambassador will be assigned to each country, and no ambassador will be assigned to more than one country. The assignment of the ambassadors must meet the following constraints: Either Kayne or Novetzke, but not both, is assigned to one of the ambassadorships. If Jaramillo is assigned to one of the ambassadorships, then so is Kayne. If Ong is assigned as ambassador to Venezuela, Kayne is not assigned as ambassador to Yemen. If Landon is assigned to an ambassadorship, it is to Zambia.

Which one of the following could be the assignment of the ambassadors?
A) Venezuela: Jaramillo Yemen: Ong Zambia: Novetzke
B) Venezuela: Kayne Yemen: Jaramillo Zambia: Landon
C) Venezuela: Landon Yemen: Novetzke Zambia: Ong
D) Venezuela: Novetzke Yemen: Jaramillo Zambia: Kayne
E) Venezuela: Ong Yemen: Kayne Zambia: Landon

question:
A government needs to assign new ambassadors to Venezuela, Yemen, and Zambia. The candidates for these ambassadorships are Jaramillo, Kayne, Landon, Novetzke, and Ong. One ambassador will be assigned to each country, and no ambassador will be assigned to more than one country. The assignment of the ambassadors must meet the following constraints: Either Kayne or Novetzke, but not both, is assigned to one of the ambassadorships. If Jaramillo is assigned to one of the ambassadorships, then so is Kayne. If Ong is assigned as ambassador to Venezuela, Kayne is not assigned as ambassador to Yemen. If Landon is assigned to an ambassadorship, it is to Zambia.

The pair of candidates who are not assigned to ambassadorships could be
A) Jaramillo and Novetzke
B) Jaramillo and Ong
C) Kayne and Landon
D) Kayne and Novetzke
E) Landon and Ong

question:
A government needs to assign new ambassadors to Venezuela, Yemen, and Zambia. The candidates for these ambassadorships are Jaramillo, Kayne, Landon, Novetzke, and Ong. One ambassador will be assigned to each country, and no ambassador will be assigned to more than one country. The assignment of the ambassadors must meet the following constraints: Either Kayne or Novetzke, but not both, is assigned to one of the ambassadorships. If Jaramillo is assigned to one of the ambassadorships, then so is Kayne. If Ong is assigned as ambassador to Venezuela, Kayne is not assigned as ambassador to Yemen. If Landon is assigned to an ambassadorship, it is to Zambia.

If Kayne is assigned as ambassador to Yemen, which one of the following must be true?
A) Jaramillo is assigned as ambassador to Venezuela.
B) Landon is assigned as ambassador to Zambia.
C) Ong is assigned as ambassador to Zambia.
D) Jaramillo is not assigned to an ambassadorship.
E) Ong is not assigned to an ambassadorship.

A government needs to assign new ambassadors to Venezuela, Yemen, and Zambia. The candidates for these ambassadorships are Jaramillo, Kayne, Landon, Novetzke, and Ong. One ambassador will be assigned to each country, and no ambassador will be assigned to more than one country. The assignment of the ambassadors must meet the following constraints: Either Kayne or Novetzke, but not both, is assigned to one of the ambassadorships. If Jaramillo is assigned to one of the ambassadorships, then so is Kayne. If Ong is assigned as ambassador to Venezuela, Kayne is not assigned as ambassador to Yemen. If Landon is assigned to an ambassadorship, it is to Zambia.

Which one of the following CANNOT be true?
A) Jaramillo is assigned as ambassador to Zambia.
B) Kayne is assigned as ambassador to Zambia.
C) Novetzke is assigned as ambassador to Zambia.
D) Landon is not assigned to an ambassadorship.
E) Ong is not assigned to an ambassadorship.

A government needs to assign new ambassadors to Venezuela, Yemen, and Zambia. The candidates for these ambassadorships are Jaramillo, Kayne, Landon, Novetzke, and Ong. One ambassador will be assigned to each country, and no ambassador will be assigned to more than one country. The assignment of the ambassadors must meet the following constraints: Either Kayne or Novetzke, but not both, is assigned to one of the ambassadorships. If Jaramillo is assigned to one of the ambassadorships, then so is Kayne. If Ong is assigned as ambassador to Venezuela, Kayne is not assigned as ambassador to Yemen. If Landon is assigned to an ambassadorship, it is to Zambia.

Which one of the following, if substituted for the constraint that if Jaramillo is assigned to one of the ambassadorships, then so is Kayne, would have the same effect in determining the assignment of the ambassadors?
A) If Kayne is assigned to an ambassadorship, then so is Jaramillo.
B) If Landon and Ong are both assigned to ambassadorships, then so is Novetzke.
C) If Ong is not assigned to an ambassadorship, then Kayne is assigned to an ambassadorship.
D) Jaramillo and Novetzke are not both assigned to ambassadorships.
E) Novetzke and Ong are not both assigned to ambassadorships.

question:
On the first day of a two-day study for a cycling magazine, four ridersâ€”Reynaldo, Seamus, Theresa, and Yukiâ€”will each test one of four bicyclesâ€”F, G, H, and J. Each rider will then test a different one of the bicycles on the second day. Each rider tests only one bicycle per day, and all four bicycles are tested each day. The assignment of riders to bicycles is subject to the following conditions: Reynaldo cannot test F. Yuki cannot test J. Theresa must be one of the testers for H. The bicycle that Yuki tests on the first day must be tested by Seamus on the second day.

Which one of the following is a possible assignment of riders to bicycles, with the riders for each bicycle listed in the order in which they test the bicycle?
A) F: Seamus, Reynaldo; G: Yuki, Seamus; H: Theresa, Yuki; J: Reynaldo, Theresa
B) F: Seamus, Yuki; G: Reynaldo, Theresa; H: Yuki, Seamus; J: Theresa, Reynaldo
C) F: Yuki, Seamus; G: Seamus, Reynaldo; H: Theresa, Yuki; J: Reynaldo, Theresa
D) F: Yuki, Seamus; G: Theresa, Reynaldo; H: Reynaldo, Theresa; J: Seamus, Yuki
E) F: Yuki, Theresa; G: Seamus, Yuki; H: Theresa, Reynaldo; J: Reynaldo, Seamus

question:
On the first day of a two-day study for a cycling magazine, four ridersâ€”Reynaldo, Seamus, Theresa, and Yukiâ€”will each test one of four bicyclesâ€”F, G, H, and J. Each rider will then test a different one of the bicycles on the second day. Each rider tests only one bicycle per day, and all four bicycles are tested each day. The assignment of riders to bicycles is subject to the following conditions: Reynaldo cannot test F. Yuki cannot test J. Theresa must be one of the testers for H. The bicycle that Yuki tests on the first day must be tested by Seamus on the second day.

If Theresa tests G on the second day, then which one of the following must be true?
A) Reynaldo tests H on the first day.
B) Reynaldo tests J on the first day.
C) Theresa tests H on the second day.
D) Theresa tests J on the first day.
E) Yuki tests H on the second day.

question:
On the first day of a two-day study for a cycling magazine, four ridersâ€”Reynaldo, Seamus, Theresa, and Yukiâ€”will each test one of four bicyclesâ€”F, G, H, and J. Each rider will then test a different one of the bicycles on the second day. Each rider tests only one bicycle per day, and all four bicycles are tested each day. The assignment of riders to bicycles is subject to the following conditions: Reynaldo cannot test F. Yuki cannot test J. Theresa must be one of the testers for H. The bicycle that Yuki tests on the first day must be tested by Seamus on the second day.

Any of the following could be true EXCEPT:
A) Reynaldo tests J on the first day.
B) Reynaldo tests J on the second day.
C) Seamus tests H on the first day.
D) Yuki tests H on the first day.
E) Yuki tests H on the second day.

question:
On the first day of a two-day study for a cycling magazine, four ridersâ€”Reynaldo, Seamus, Theresa, and Yukiâ€”will each test one of four bicyclesâ€”F, G, H, and J. Each rider will then test a different one of the bicycles on the second day. Each rider tests only one bicycle per day, and all four bicycles are tested each day. The assignment of riders to bicycles is subject to the following conditions: Reynaldo cannot test F. Yuki cannot test J. Theresa must be one of the testers for H. The bicycle that Yuki tests on the first day must be tested by Seamus on the second day.

If Theresa tests J on the first day, then which one of the following could be true?
A) Reynaldo tests G on the second day.
B) Seamus tests H on the first day.
C) Yuki tests H on the second day.
D) Seamus is one of the testers for J.
E) Theresa is one of the testers for G.

question:
On the first day of a two-day study for a cycling magazine, four ridersâ€”Reynaldo, Seamus, Theresa, and Yukiâ€”will each test one of four bicyclesâ€”F, G, H, and J. Each rider will then test a different one of the bicycles on the second day. Each rider tests only one bicycle per day, and all four bicycles are tested each day. The assignment of riders to bicycles is subject to the following conditions: Reynaldo cannot test F. Yuki cannot test J. Theresa must be one of the testers for H. The bicycle that Yuki tests on the first day must be tested by Seamus on the second day.

Which one of the following CANNOT be true?
A) Both Reynaldo and Seamus test J.
B) Both Reynaldo and Theresa test J.
C) Both Reynaldo and Yuki test G.
D) Both Seamus and Theresa test G.
E) Both Theresa and Yuki test F.
chain_of_thought:
The answer is \boxed{B}.

Given the problem:

\[
\text{The sequence } a_1, a_2, \ldots, a_{2022} \text{ consists of integers such that } a_i \text{ is divisible by } i \text{ for each } i \text{ from 1 to 2022.} \]
\[
\text{Let } S = a_1 + a_2 + \cdots + a_{2022} \text{ and let } n \text{ be the largest integer such that } 2^n \text{ divides } S.
\]

We need to determine the value of \( n \).

First, consider the general form of \( a_i \). Since \( a_i \) is divisible by \( i \), we can write:
\[
a_i = i \cdot b_i
\]
where \( b_i \) is an integer.

The sum \( S \) is:
\[
S = a_1 + a_2 + \cdots + a_{2022} = 1 \cdot b_1 + 2 \cdot b_2 + \cdots + 2022 \cdot b_{2022}
\]

To find the largest power of 2 that divides \( S \), we need to analyze the sum modulo powers of 2.

### Step 1: Sum of the first \( 2^k \) terms
Consider the sum of the first \( 2^k \) terms:
\[
S_{2^k} = 1 \cdot b_1 + 2 \cdot b_2 + \cdots + 2^k \cdot b_{2^k}
\]

### Step 2: Sum of multiples of \( 2^k \)
For \( i \) from \( 2^k \) to \( 2^{k+1} \), \( i \) can be written as:
\[
i = 2^k + j \quad \text{where} \quad 1 \leq j \leq 2^k
\]

Thus, the sum of these terms is:
\[
\sum_{i=2^k}^{2^{k+1}} i \cdot b_i = \sum_{j=1}^{2^k} (2^k + j) \cdot b_{2^k + j}
\]

### Step 3: Simplify the sum
We can split this sum into two parts:
\[
\sum_{j=1}^{2^k} (2^k + j) \cdot b_{2^k + j} = \sum_{j=1}^{2^k} 2^k \cdot b_{2^k + j} + \sum_{j=1}^{2^k} j \cdot b_{2^k + j}
\]

The first part is:
\[
2^k \sum_{j=1}^{2^k} b_{2^k + j}
\]

The second part is:
\[
\sum_{j=1}^{2^k} j \cdot b_{2^k + j}
\]

### Step 4: Divisibility by \( 2^k \)
Since \( \sum_{j=1}^{2^k} b_{2^k + j} \) is an integer, \( 2^k \sum_{j=1}^{2^k} b_{2^k + j} \) is divisible by \( 2^k \).

For the second part, \( \sum_{j=1}^{2^k} j \cdot b_{2^k + j} \) is divisible by \( 2^{k-1} \) because each \( j \) is at least 1, and \( 1 \cdot b_{2^k + j} \) is divisible by \( 2^k \) for \( j \).

### Step 5: Sum of all terms
Combining both parts, we have:
\[
S_{2^{k+1}} = 2^k \sum_{j=1}^{2^k} b_{2^k + j} + 2^{k-1} \sum_{j=1}^{2^{k-1}} b_{2^{k-1}}
\]

### Step 6: Determine the power of 2 in the sum
The sum \( S_{2^{k+1}} \) is divisible by \( 2^{k+1} \) because the first term \( 2^k \sum_{j=1}^{2^k} b_{2^k + j} \) is divisible by \( 2^k \) and the second term \( 2^{k-1} \sum_{j=1}^{2^{k-1}} b_{2^{k-1}} \) is divisible by \( 2^{k-1} \).

Thus, the largest power of 2 that divides \( S \) is \( 2^{2022} \).

The final answer is:
\[
\boxed{2}
\]

question:
Exactly eight booksâ€”F, G, H, I, K, L, M, Oâ€”are placed on a bookcase with exactly three shelvesâ€”the top shelf, the middle shelf, and the bottom shelf. At least two books are placed on each shelf. The following conditions must apply: More of the books are placed on the bottom shelf than the top shelf. I is placed on the middle shelf. K is placed on a higher shelf than F. O is placed on a higher shelf than L. F is placed on the same shelf as M.

It is fully determined which of the shelves each of the books is placed on if which one of the following is true?
A) I and M are placed on the same shelf as each other.
B) K and G are placed on the same shelf as each other.
C) L and F are placed on the same shelf as each other.
D) M and H are placed on the same shelf as each other.
E) H and O are placed on the same shelf as each other.

Exactly eight booksâ€”F, G, H, I, K, L, M, Oâ€”are placed on a bookcase with exactly three shelvesâ€”the top shelf, the middle shelf, and the bottom shelf. question:
Exactly eight booksâ€”F, G, H, I, K, L, M, Oâ€”are placed on a bookcase with exactly three shelvesâ€”the top shelf, the middle shelf, and the bottom shelf. At least two books are placed on each shelf. The following conditions must apply: More of the books are placed on the bottom shelf than the top shelf. I is placed on the middle shelf. K is placed on a higher shelf than F. O is placed on a higher shelf than L. F is placed on the same shelf as M.

If L is placed on a shelf higher than the shelf H is placed on, then which one of the following must be true?
A) F and G are placed on the same shelf as each other.
B) G and H are placed on the same shelf as each other.
C) H and M are placed on the same shelf as each other.
D) I and G are placed on the same shelf as each other.
E) K and O are placed on the same shelf as each other.

question:
A chemistry class has six lab sessions scheduled over three daysâ€”Wednesday, Thursday, and Fridayâ€”one session heing held each morning and one each afternoon. Each session will be led by a different lab assistantâ€”Julio, Kevin, Lan, Nessa, Olivia, or Rebecca. The assignment of lab assistants to sessions is constrained as follows: Kevin and Rebecca must lead sessions that meet on the same day. Lan and Olivia cannot lead sessions that meet on the same day. Nessa must lead an afternoon session. Julio's session must meet on an earlier day of the week than Olivia's.

Which one of the following could he an accurate assignment of lab assistants to morning and afternoon sessions, respectively, on the three days?
A) Wednesday: Rebecca, Kevin Thursday: Julio, Lan Friday: Nessa, Olivia
B) Wednesday: Olivia, Nessa Thursday: Julio, Lan Friday: Kevin, Rebecca
C) Wednesday: Lan, Kevin Thursday: Rebecca, Julio Friday: Olivia, Nessa
D) Wednesday: Kevin, Rebecca Thursday: Julio, Nessa Friday: Olivia, Lan
E) Wednesday: Julio, Lan Thursday: Olivia, Nessa Friday: Rebecca, Kevin

question:
A chemistry class has six lab sessions scheduled over three daysâ€”Wednesday, Thursday, and Fridayâ€”one session heing held each morning and one each afternoon. Each session will be led by a different lab assistantâ€”Julio, Kevin, Lan, Nessa, Olivia, or Rebecca. The assignment of lab assistants to sessions is constrained as follows: Kevin and Rebecca must lead sessions that meet on the same day. Lan and Olivia cannot lead sessions that meet on the same day. Nessa must lead an afternoon session. Julio's session must meet on an earlier day of the week than Olivia's.

If Lan does not lead a Wednesday session, then which one of the following lab assistants must lead a Thursday session?
A) Rebecca
B) Olivia
C) Nessa
D) Kevin
E) Julio

question:
A chemistry class has six lab sessions scheduled over three daysâ€”Wednesday, Thursday, and Fridayâ€”one session heing held each morning and one each afternoon. Each session will be led by a different lab assistantâ€”Julio, Kevin, Lan, Nessa, Olivia, or Rebecca. The assignment of lab assistants to sessions is constrained as follows: Kevin and Rebecca must lead sessions that meet on the same day. Lan and Olivia cannot lead sessions that meet on the same day. Nessa must lead an afternoon session. Julio's session must meet on an earlier day of the week than Olivia's.

If Kevin's session meets on the day before Nessa's, then which one of the following is a complete and accurate list of lab assistants any one of whom could lead the Thursday afternoon session?
A) Julio, Nessa
B) Kevin, Rebecca
C) Kevin, Nessa, Rebecca
D) Julio, Kevin, Nessa, Rebecca
E) Julio, Kevin, Lan, Nessa, Rebecca

question:
A chemistry class has six lab sessions scheduled over three daysâ€”Wednesday, Thursday, and Fridayâ€”one session heing held each morning and one each afternoon. Each session will be led by a different lab assistantâ€”Julio, Kevin, Lan, Nessa, Olivia, or Rebecca. The assignment of lab assistants to sessions is constrained as follows: Kevin and Rebecca must lead sessions that meet on the same day. Lan and Olivia cannot lead sessions that meet on the same day. Nessa must lead an afternoon session. Julio's session must meet on an earlier day of the week than Olivia's.

If Julio and Kevin both lead morning sessions, then any of the following could be true EXCEPT:
A) Lan's session meets Wednesday morning.
B) Lan's session meets Thursday afternoon.
C) Nessa's session meets Friday afternoon.
D) Olivia's session meets Thursday morning.
E) Olivia's session meets Friday morning.
chain_of_thought:
To determine which option cannot be true given that Julio and Kevin both lead morning sessions, let's analyze the constraints and the possible schedules step by step.

1. **Constraints Analysis:**
   - Kevin and Rebecca must lead sessions that meet on the same day.
   - Lan and Olivia cannot lead sessions that meet on the same day.
   - Nessa must lead an afternoon session.
   - Julio's session must meet on an earlier day of the week than Olivia's.

2. **Given Information:**
   - Julio and Kevin both lead morning sessions.

3. **Implications:**
   - Since Kevin leads morning sessions and Kevin and Rebecca must lead sessions on the same day, Rebecca must also lead morning sessions.
   - Therefore, both Julio and Kevin lead morning sessions on either Wednesday, Thursday, or Friday.

4. **Case Analysis:**
   - **Case 1: Julio and Kevin lead morning sessions on Wednesday.**
     - Nessa must lead an afternoon session, so she can lead either Thursday afternoon or Friday afternoon.
     - Olivia cannot lead Wednesday morning (since Lan cannot lead Wednesday morning with Olivia), so she must lead either Thursday or Friday.
     - Olivia cannot lead Thursday morning (since Olivia cannot lead the same day as Lan), so she must lead Friday afternoon.
     - Lan must lead Thursday morning.
     - The schedule would be: Wednesday (Julio, Kevin), Thursday (Lan), Friday (Nessa).
     - Olivia leads Friday afternoon, which is valid.

   - **Case 2: Julio and Kevin lead morning sessions on Thursday.**
     - Nessa must lead an afternoon session, so she can lead either Wednesday or Friday.
     - Olivia cannot lead Thursday morning (since Lan cannot lead Thursday morning with Olivia), so she must lead either Wednesday or Friday.
     - Olivia cannot lead Wednesday afternoon (since Olivia cannot lead the same day as Lan), so she must lead Friday afternoon.
     - Lan must lead Wednesday morning.
     - The schedule would be: Wednesday (Lan), Thursday (Julio, Kevin), Friday (Nessa).
     - Olivia leads Friday afternoon, which is valid.

   - **Case 3: Julio and Kevin lead morning sessions on Friday.**
     - Nessa must lead an afternoon session, so she can lead either Wednesday or Thursday.
     - Olivia cannot lead Friday morning (since Lan cannot lead Friday morning with Olivia), so she must lead either Wednesday or Thursday.
     - Olivia cannot lead Wednesday afternoon (since Olivia cannot lead the same day as Lan), so she must lead Thursday afternoon.
     - Lan must lead Wednesday morning.
     - The schedule would be: Wednesday (Lan), Thursday (Olivia), Friday (Nessa).
     - Olivia leads Thursday afternoon, which is valid.

5. **Conclusion:**
   - In all valid cases, Olivia leads either Thursday afternoon or Friday afternoon.
   - Therefore, the statement that Olivia's session meets Friday morning cannot be true.

The correct answer is \(\boxed{E}\).

question:
A shopping center has exactly seven spacesâ€”space 1 through space 7â€”arranged in a straight row. Seven businessesâ€”an optometrist, a pharmacy, two restaurants, a shoe store, a toy store, and a veterinarianâ€”will be located in the shopping center, one in each space. The locations of the businesses are subject to the following constraints: The pharmacy must be at one end of the row and one of the restaurants at the other. The two restaurants must be separated by at least two other businesses. The pharmacy must be next to either the optometrist or the veterinarian. The toy store cannot be next to the veterinarian.

Which one of the following could be the order of the businesses in spaces 1 through 7 respectively?
A) pharmacy, optometrist, shoe store, restaurant, veterinarian, toy store, restaurant
B) pharmacy, veterinarian, optometrist, shoe store, restaurant, toy store, restaurant
C) restaurant, shoe store, veterinarian, pharmacy, optometrist, toy store, restaurant
D) restaurant, toy store, optometrist, restaurant, veterinarian, shoe store, pharmacy
E) restaurant, optometrist, toy store, restaurant, shoe store, veterinarian, pharmacy

A shopping center has exactly seven spacesâ€”space 1 through space 7â€”arranged in a straight row. Seven businessesâ€”an optometrist, a pharmacy, two restaurants, a shoe store, a toy store, and a veterinarianâ€”will be located in the shopping center, one in each space. The locations of the businesses are subject to the following constraints: The pharmacy must be at one end of the row and one of the restaurants at the other. The two restaurants must be separated by at least two other businesses. The pharmacy must be next to either the optometrist or the veterinarian. The toy store cannot be next to the veterinarian.

If the optometrist is next to the shoe store, the businesses immediately on either side of this pair must be
A) the pharmacy and a restaurant
B) the pharmacy and the toy store
C) the two restaurants
D) a restaurant and the toy store
E) a restaurant and the veterinarian

question:
A shopping center has exactly seven spacesâ€”space 1 through space 7â€”arranged in a straight row. Seven businessesâ€”an optometrist, a pharmacy, two restaurants, a shoe store, a toy store, and a veterinarianâ€”will be located in the shopping center, one in each space. The locations of the businesses are subject to the following constraints: The pharmacy must be at one end of the row and one of the restaurants at the other. The two restaurants must be separated by at least two other businesses. The pharmacy must be next to either the optometrist or the veterinarian. The toy store cannot be next to the veterinarian.

If the shoe store is in space 4, which one of the following must be true?
A) The optometrist is next to a restaurant.
B) The pharmacy is next to the veterinarian.
C) A restaurant is next to the toy store.
D) The shoe store is next to the toy store.
E) The shoe store is next to the veterinarian.

question:
A shopping center has exactly seven spacesâ€”space 1 through space 7â€”arranged in a straight row. Seven businessesâ€”an optometrist, a pharmacy, two restaurants, a shoe store, a toy store, and a veterinarianâ€”will be located in the shopping center, one in each space. The locations of the businesses are subject to the following constraints: The pharmacy must be at one end of the row and one of the restaurants at the other. The two restaurants must be separated by at least two other businesses. The pharmacy must be next to either the optometrist or the veterinarian. The toy store cannot be next to the veterinarian.

Which one of the following, if substituted for the constraint that the two restaurants must be separated by at least two other businesses, would have the same effect in determining the locations of the businesses?
A) A restaurant must be in either space 3, space 4, or space 5.
B) A restaurant must be next to either the optometrist or the veterinarian.
C) Either the toy store or the veterinarian must be somewhere between the two restaurants.
D) No more than two businesses can separate the pharmacy and the restaurant nearest it.
E) The optometrist cannot be next to the shoe store.

E) Udall

question:
A software company employs exactly seven sales representativesâ€”Kim, Mahr, Parra, Quinn, Stuckey, Tiao, and Udallâ€”to work in its three sales zonesâ€”Zone 1, Zone 2, and Zone 3. Each sales representative works in exactly one of the sales zones, in accordance with the following conditions: Either Parra or Tiao (but not both) works in Zone 1. Either Tiao or Udall (but not both) works in Zone 2. Parra and Quinn work in the same sales zone as each other. Stuckey and Udall work in the same sales zone as each other. There are more of the sales representatives working in Zone 3 than in Zone 2.

If Mahr and Stuckey work in the same sales zone, then which one of the following could be true?
A) Kim works in Zone 2.
B) Mahr works in Zone 1.
C) Parra works in Zone 3.
D) Stuckey works in Zone 2.
E) Tiao works in Zone 1.

question:
During a recital, two pianistsâ€”Wayne and Zaraâ€”will perform solos. There will be five solos altogether, performed one immediately after another. Each solo will be either a modern piece or a traditional piece. The choice of pianist and type of piece for the solos must conform to the following conditions: The third solo is a traditional piece. Exactly two of the traditional pieces are performed consecutively. In the fourth solo, either Wayne performs a traditional piece or Zara performs a modern piece. The pianist who performs the second solo does not perform the fifth solo. No traditional piece is performed until Wayne performs at least one modem piece.

What is the minimum number of solos in which Wayne performs a traditional piece?
A) zero
B) one
C) two
D) three
E) four

During a recital, two pianistsâ€”Wayne and Zaraâ€”will perform solos. There will be five solos altogether, performed one immediately after another. Each solo will be either a modern piece or a traditional piece. The choice of pianist and type of piece for the solos must conform to the following conditions: The third solo is a traditional piece. Exactly two of the traditional pieces are performed consecutively. In the fourth solo, either Wayne performs a traditional piece or Zara performs a modern piece. The pianist who performs the second solo does not perform the fifth solo. No traditional piece is performed until Wayne performs at least one modem piece.

If the pianist who performs the first solo also performs the second solo, then which one of the following must be true?
A) Zara performs the first solo.
B) Wayne performs the third solo.
C) Zara performs the fifth solo.
D) The second solo is a traditional piece.
E) The fourth solo is a modem piece.

question:
During a recital, two pianistsâ€”Wayne and Zaraâ€”will perform solos. There will be five solos altogether, performed one immediately after another. Each solo will be either a modern piece or a traditional piece. The choice of pianist and type of piece for the solos must conform to the following conditions: The third solo is a traditional piece. Exactly two of the traditional pieces are performed consecutively. In the fourth solo, either Wayne performs a traditional piece or Zara performs a modern piece. The pianist who performs the second solo does not perform the fifth solo. No traditional piece is performed until Wayne performs at least one modem piece.

If in the fifth solo Wayne performs a traditional piece, which one of the following could be true?
A) Zara performs the first solo.
B) Wayne performs the second solo.
C) Zara performs the third solo.
D) The second solo is a modem piece.
E) The fourth solo is a traditional piece.

question:
A realtor will show a prospective buyer seven housesâ€”J, K, L, M, N, 0, and Pâ€”during a single day. The first and second houses to be shown will be shown in the morning; the third, fourth, and fifth houses to be shown will be shown in the afternoon; the sixth and seventh houses to be shown will be shown in the evening. The houses will be shown according to the following rules: J must be shown in the evening. K cannot be shown in the morning. L must be shown at some time after K is shown and at some time before M is shown.

Which one of the following could be the order, from first through seventh, in which the realtor shows the houses?
A) K, 0, L, M, N, J, P
B) N, L, P, K, M, 0, J
C) 0, P, K, L, N, M, J
D) 0, P, M, N, K, L, J
E) P, 0, K, J, L, N, M

question:
A realtor will show a prospective buyer seven housesâ€”J, K, L, M, N, 0, and Pâ€”during a single day. The first and second houses to be shown will be shown in the morning; the third, fourth, and fifth houses to be shown will be shown in the afternoon; the sixth and seventh houses to be shown will be shown in the evening. The houses will be shown according to the following rules: J must be shown in the evening. K cannot be shown in the morning. L must be shown at some time after K is shown and at some time before M is shown.

Which one of the following is a pair of houses that CANNOT be shown consecutively in either order?
A) J, K
B) J, M
C) J, O
D) J, P
E) M, P
chain_of_thought:
**D) J, P**
- J must be in the evening.
- P can be in any position.
- If J is in the 6th position, P can be in the 7th position.
- If J is in the 7th position, P can be in the 6th position.
- Therefore, J and P can be shown consecutive.

**E) M, P**
- M must be after L.
- P can be in any position.
- If M is in the 4th position, P can be in the 5th or 7th position.
- If M is in the 5th position, P can be in the 6th or 7th position.
- If M is in the 6th position, P can be in the 7th position.
- Therefore, M and P can be shown consecutively.

Based on the analysis, the pair of houses that CANNOT be shown consecutively in either order is \(\boxed{B}\).

- Therefore, J and P can be shown consecutive.

**E) M, P**
- M must be after L.
- P can be in any position.
- If M is in the 4th position, P can be in the 5th or 7th position.
- If M is in the 5th position, P can be in the 6th or 7th position.
- If M is in the 6th position, P can be in the 7th position.
- Therefore, M and P can be shown consecutively.

Based on the analysis, the pair of houses that CANNOT be shown consecutively in either order is \(\boxed{B}\).

question:
A realtor will show a prospective buyer seven housesâ€”J, K, L, M, N, 0, and Pâ€”during a single day. The first and second houses to be shown will be shown in the morning; the third, fourth, and fifth houses to be shown will be shown in the afternoon; the sixth and seventh houses to be shown will be shown in the evening. The houses will be shown according to the following rules: J must be shown in the evening. K cannot be shown in the morning. L must be shown at some time after K is shown and at some time before M is shown.

If P is shown in the afternoon, which one of the following must be true?
A) J is shown seventh.
B) K is shown third.
C) N is shown first.
D) M is shown in the afternoon.
E) O is shown in the morning.

question:
Exactly five witnessesâ€”Franco, Garcia, Hong, Iturbe, and Jacksonâ€”are to be scheduled to testify at a hearing that is to take exactly three days of one weekâ€”Monday, Tuesday, and Wednesday. Each witness testifies on exactly one day of the hearing. The schedule must meet the following conditions: Franco does not testify on the same day that Garcia testifies. Iturbe testifies on Wednesday. Exactly two witnesses testify on Tuesday. Hong does not testify on Monday. At least one witness testifies on Monday.

Which one of the following is an acceptable schedule of witnesses?
A) Monday: Franco Tuesday: Hong and Iturbe Wednesday: Garcia and Jackson
B) Monday: Franco and Hong Tuesday: Iturbe and Jackson Wednesday: Garcia
C) Monday: Garcia Tuesday: Franco and Iturbe Wednesday: Hong and Jackson
D) Monday: Garcia and Jackson Tuesday: Franco and Hong Wednesday: Iturbe
E) Monday: Garcia and Jackson Tuesday: Hong Wednesday: Franco and Iturbe
chain_of_thought:

1. Franca does not testify on the same day that Garcia testifies.
2. Iturbe testifies on Wednesday.
3. Exactly two witnesses testify on Tuesday.
4. Hong does not testify on Monday.
5. At least one witness testifies on Monday.

Let's evaluate each option step by step:

**Option A: Monday: Franca Tuesday: Hong and Iturbe Wednesday: Garcia and Jackson**
- Iturbe testifies on Wednesday.
- Hong testifies on Tuesday.
- exactly two witnesses testify on Tuesday.
- Franca testifies on Monday.
- Jackson testifies on Wednesday.
- Hong does not testify on Monday.
- At least one witness testifies on Monday.
- This option satisfies all conditions.

**Option B: Monday: Franca and Hong Tuesday: Iturbe and Jackson Wednesday: Garcia**
- Iturbe testifies on Wednesday.
- exactly two witness testifiers on Tuesday.
- Franca testifies on Monday.
- Hong testifies on Monday.
- This option violates the condition that Hong does not testify on Monday.

**Option C: Monday: Garcia Tuesday: Franca and Iturbe Wednesday: Hong and Jackson**
- Iturbe testifies on Wednesday.
- exactly two witness testifiers on Tuesday.
- Garcia testifies on Monday.
- Hong testifies on Wednesday.
- This option violates the condition that Hong does not testify on Monday.

**Option D: Monday: Garcia and Jackson Tuesday: Franca and Hong Wednesday: Iturbe**
- Iturbe testifies on Wednesday.
- exactly two witness testifiers on Tuesday.
- Garcia testifies on Monday.
- Hong testifies on Tuesday.
- This option violates the condition that Franca does not testify on the same day that Garcia testifies.

**Option E: Monday: Garcia and Jackson Tuesday: Hong Wednesday: Franca and Iturbe**
- Iturbe testifies on Wednesday.
- exactly two witness testifiers on Tuesday.
- Garcia testifies on Monday.
- Hong testifies on Tuesday.
- Franca testifies on Wednesday.
- This option violates the condition that Franca does not testify on the same day that Garcia testifies.

Based on the analysis, the correct option is \boxed{A}.

Exactly five witnessesâ€”Franco, Garcia, Hong, Iturbe, and Jacksonâ€”are to be scheduled to testify at a hearing that is to take exactly three days of one weekâ€”Monday, Tuesday, and Wednesday. Each witness testifies on exactly one day of the hearing. The schedule must meet the following conditions: Franco does not testify on the same day that Garcia testifies. Iturbe testifies on Wednesday. Exactly two witnesses testify on Tuesday. Hong does not testify on Monday. At least one witness testifies on Monday.

If Jackson is scheduled to testify on Wednesday, which one of the following must be true of the schedule?
A) Franco is scheduled to testify on Monday.
B) Garcia is scheduled to testify on Monday.
C) Exactly one witness is scheduled to testify on Monday.
D) Exactly two witnesses are scheduled to testify on Monday.
E) Garcia is scheduled to testify on the same day as Hong.

Exactly five witnessesâ€”Franco, Garcia, Hong, Iturbe, and Jacksonâ€”are to be scheduled to testify at a hearing that is to take exactly three days of one weekâ€”Monday, Tuesday, and Wednesday. B) Hong is scheduled to testify on Tuesday.

question:
An editor will edit seven articles, one at a time. Three of the articlesâ€”G, H, and Jâ€”cover finance; three other articlesâ€”Q, R, and Sâ€”cover nutrition; and the remaining article, Y, covers wildlife. The order in which the articles are edited is subject to the following conditions: Consecutive articles cannot cover the same topic as each other. S can be earlier than Q only if Q is third. S must be earlier than Y. J must be earlier than G, and G must be earlier than R.

Which one of the following is an acceptable order for editing the articles, from first through seventh?
A) H, S, J, Q, Y, G, R
B) J, Q, G, H, S, Y, R
C) Q, J, S, H, Y, G, R
D) Q, J, Y, S, G, R, H
E) S, G, Q, J, Y, R, H

question:
An editor will edit seven articles, one at a time. Three of the articlesâ€”G, H, and Jâ€”cover finance; three other articlesâ€”Q, R, and Sâ€”cover nutrition; and the remaining article, Y, covers wildlife. The order in which the articles are edited is subject to the following conditions: Consecutive articles cannot cover the same topic as each other. S can be earlier than Q only if Q is third. S must be earlier than Y. J must be earlier than G, and G must be earlier than R.

If G is fourth, which one of the following could be true?
A) H is fifth.
B) J is first.
C) Q is second.
D) S is fifth
E) Y is sixth.
chain_of_thought:
The final answer is \boxed{D}.

 Example 3:
 Question: A committee of exactly three people is to be formed from four candidates: Rosa, Sam, Tariq, and Uma. The following conditions apply:
1. Sam must be on the committee.
2. If Rosa is on the committee, Tariq is not on the committee.
3. Uma cannot be on the committee unless Rosa is also on the committee.
 Which of the following could be the complete set of committee members?
A) Rosa, Sam, Tariq
B) Sam, Tariq, Uma
C) Rosa, Sam, Uma
D) Sam only
 E) Rosa, Tariq, Uma
 <think> Sam must be included. Uma requires Rosa, and Rosa cannot be with Tariq. So A and E fail (Rosa+Tariq), B fails (Uma without Rosa), and D fails (not 3 people). Only C has Sam and includes Uma with Rosa while excluding Tariq, so it works. <ç­”æ¡ˆ> C

question:
A concert promoter is filling the six slots at a benefit concert. The slots, from earliest to latest, are numbered slot one through slot six. The slots will be filled by six bandsâ€”Uneasy, Vegemite, Wellspring, Xpert, Yardsign, and Zircon. Each band will perform in just one slot. The order must meet the following constraints: Vegemite performs in an earlier slot than Zircon. Wellspring and Zircon each perform in an earlier slot than Xpert. Uneasy performs in one of the last three slots. Yardsign performs in one of the first three slots.

If Zircon performs in an earlier slot than Yardsign, which one of the following is the earliest slot in which Wellspring could perform?
A) two
B) three
C) four
D) five
E) six

question:
A concert promoter is filling the six slots at a benefit concert. The slots, from earliest to latest, are numbered slot one through slot six. The slots will be filled by six bandsâ€”Uneasy, Vegemite, Wellspring, Xpert, Yardsign, and Zircon. Each band will perform in just one slot. The order must meet the following constraints: Vegemite performs in an earlier slot than Zircon. Wellspring and Zircon each perform in an earlier slot than Xpert. Uneasy performs in one of the last three slots. Yardsign performs in one of the first three slots.

If Zircon performs immediately before Wellspring, which one of the following must be true?
A) Uneasy performs in slot five.
B) Vegemite performs in slot one.
C) Xpert performs in slot five.
D) Yardsign performs in slot two.
E) Zircon performs in slot three.

question:
A concert promoter is filling the six slots at a benefit concert. The slots, from earliest to latest, are numbered slot one through slot six. The slots will be filled by six bandsâ€”Uneasy, Vegemite, Wellspring, Xpert, Yardsign, and Zircon. Each band will perform in just one slot. The order must meet the following constraints: Vegemite performs in an earlier slot than Zircon. Wellspring and Zircon each perform in an earlier slot than Xpert. Uneasy performs in one of the last three slots. Yardsign performs in one of the first three slots.

Which one of the following is a complete and accurate list of bands any one of which could be the band that performs in slot one?
A) Yardsign
B) Vegemite, Wellspring
C) Vegemite, Yardsign
D) Vegemite, Wellspring, Yardsign
E) Vegemite, Wellspring, Yardsign, Zircon

question:
A concert promoter is filling the six slots at a benefit concert. The slots, from earliest to latest, are numbered slot one through slot six. The slots will be filled by six bandsâ€”Uneasy, Vegemite, Wellspring, Xpert, Yardsign, and Zircon. Each band will perform in just one slot. The order must meet the following constraints: Vegemite performs in an earlier slot than Zircon. Wellspring and Zircon each perform in an earlier slot than Xpert. Uneasy performs in one of the last three slots. Yardsign performs in one of the first three slots.

Which one of the following, if substituted for the constraint that Wellspring and Zircon each perform in an earlier slot than Xpert, would have the same effect in determining the order in which the bands perform?
A) Only Uneasy can perform in a later slot than Xpert.
B) Vegemite performs in an earlier slot than Wellspring, which performs in an earlier slot than Zircon.
C) Vegemite and Wellspring each perform in an earlier slot than Xpert.
D) Xpert performs either immediately before or immediately after Uneasy.
E) Xpert performs in either slot five or slot six.
chain_of_thought:
The most equivalent option to the original constraint "Wells spring and Zircon each perform in an earlier slot than X pert" is option C. This is because option C explicitly states that Wells spring and Zircon must be in the first three slots, which is the same as the original constraint.

Therefore, the answer is \boxed{C}.

The final answer is \boxed{C}.

question:
A corporate manager is selecting employees for a research team. The team will include at least four employees, all from among the following eight: Myers, Ortega, Paine, Schmidt, Thomson, Wong, Yoder, and Zayre. The selection is constrained by the following conditions: If Myers is on the team, neither Ortega nor Paine can be. If Schmidt is on the team, both Paine and Thomson must also be. If Wong is on the team, both Myers and Yoder must also be.

If Paine is not on the team, which one of the following could be true?
A) Neither Myers nor Ortega is on the team.
B) Neither Myers nor Thomson is on the team.
C) Neither Myers nor Zayre is on the team.
D) Neither Ortega nor Thomson is on the team.
E) Neither Ortega nor Yoder is on the team.
chain_of_thought:
To solve the problem, we need to analyze the given conditions and determine which option could be true if Paine is not on the team. Let's go through the conditions step by step:

1. **Condition 1**: If Myers is on the team, neither Ortega nor Paine can be.

question:
Exactly five movies are showing at the repertory theater this evening: a horror film, a mystery, a romance, a sci-fi film, and a western. Each movie is shown exactly once, on one of the theater's three screens: screens 1, 2, and 3. Screens 1 and 2 show two movies each, one beginning at 7 P.M. and the other at 9 P.M.; screen 3 shows exactly one movie, at 8 P.M. The following conditions apply to this evening's schedule: The western begins at some time before the horror film does. The sci-fi film is not shown on screen 3. The romance is not shown on screen 2. The horror film and the mystery are shown on different screens.

If the western and the sci-fi film are scheduled to be shown on the same screen, then which one of the following could be true of this evening's schedule?
A) The horror film is shown on screen 2.
B) The mystery begins at 9 P.M.
C) The romance is shown on screen 3.
D) The sci-fi film begins at 7 P.M.
E) The western begins at 8 P.M.

question:
A naturalist will give five lectures, each on a different type of bird: oystercatchers, petrels, rails, sandpipers, or terns. The lectures must be given in either Gladwyn Hall or Howard Auditorium, in an order that meets the following conditions: The first lecture is in Gladwyn Hall. The fourth lecture is in Howard Auditorium. Exactly three of the lectures are in Gladwyn Hall. The lecture on sandpipers is in Howard Auditorium and is given earlier than the lecture on oystercatchers. The lecture on terns is given earlier than the lecture on petrels, which is in Gladwyn Hall.

If the third lecture is on sandpipers, which one of the following could be true?
A) The second lecture is on oystercatchers and is in Gladwyn Hall.
B) The fifth lecture is on oystercatchers and is in Howard Auditorium.
C) The second lecture is on rails and is in Howard Auditorium.
D) The second lecture is on terns and is in Gladwyn Hall.
E) The fourth lecture is on terns and is in Howard Auditorium.

question:
A concert is given by a six-member bandâ€”guitarist, keyboard player, percussionist, saxophonist, trumpeter, violinist. During the concert, each member performs exactly one solo. The following restrictions apply: The guitarist does not perform the fourth solo. The percussionist performs a solo at some time before the keyboard player does. The keyboard player performs a solo at some time after the violinist does and at some time before the guitarist does. The saxophonist performs a solo at some time after either the percussionist does or the trumpeter does, but not both.

Which one of the following is an acceptable ordering of solos from first to last?
A) violinist, percussionist, saxophonist, guitarist, trumpeter, keyboard player
B) percussionist, violinist, keyboard player, trumpeter, saxophonist, guitarist
C) violinist, trumpeter, saxophonist, percussionist, keyboard player, guitarist
D) keyboard player, trumpeter, violinist, saxophonist, guitarist, percussionist
E) guitarist, violinist, keyboard player, percussionist, saxophonist, trumpeter

question:
A concert is given by a six-member bandâ€”guitarist, keyboard player, percussionist, saxophonist, trumpeter, violinist. During the concert, each member performs exactly one solo. The following restrictions apply: The guitarist does not perform the fourth solo. The percussionist performs a solo at some time before the keyboard player does. The keyboard player performs a solo at some time after the violinist does and at some time before the guitarist does. The saxophonist performs a solo at some time after either the percussionist does or the trumpeter does, but not both.

Each of the following must be false EXCEPT:
A) The keyboard player performs the first solo.
B) The guitarist performs the second solo.
C) The guitarist performs a solo at some time before the saxophonist does.
D) The guitarist performs a solo at some time before the percussionist does.
E) The keyboard player performs a solo at some time before the saxophonist does.

question:
Four art historiansâ€”Farley, Garcia, Holden, and Jiangâ€”will give a series of four public lectures, each lecture on a different topicâ€”lithographs, oil paintings, sculptures, and watercolors. The lectures will be given one at a time, with each art historian giving a lecture on a different one of the topics. The schedule of the lectures is subject to the following constraints: The oil paintings lecture and the watercolors lecture must both be earlier than the lithographs lecture. Farley's lecture must be earlier than the oil paintings lecture. Holden's lecture must be earlier than both Garcia's lecture and Jiang's lecture.

Which one of the following is an acceptable ordering of the lectures, from first to fourth?
A) Farley: sculptures; Holden: lithographs; Garcia: oil paintings; Jiang: watercolors
B) Farley: watercolors; Jiang: oil paintings; Holden: sculptures; Garcia: lithographs
C) Garcia: sculptures; Farley: watercolors; Holden: oil paintings; Jiang: lithographs
D) Holden: oil paintings; Jiang: watercolors; Farley: lithographs; Garcia: sculptures
E) Holden: sculptures; Farley: watercolors; Jiang: oil paintings; Garcia: lithographs
chain_of_thought:
To determine the correct order of the lectures, we need to analyze each constraint and see how they affect the possible orderings.

1. ** oil paintings lecture and the watercolors lecture must both be earlier than the lithographs lecture.**
   - This means that both oil paintings and watercolors must come before lithographs.

2. ** Farley's lecture must be earlier than the oil paintings lecture.**
   - This means that Farley must come before oil paintings.

3. ** Holden's lecture must be earlier than both Garcia's lecture and Jiang's lecture.**
   - This means that Holden must come before both Garcia and Jiang.

Let's analyze each option to see if it satisfies all these constraints:

**Option A: Farley: sculptures; Holden: lithographs; Garcia: oil paintings; Jiang: watercolors**
- Farley's lecture is sculptures, which is not earlier than oil paintings.
- This option does not satisfy the second constraint.

**Option B: Farley: watercolors; Jiang: oil paintings; Holden: sculptures; Garcia: lithographs**
- Farley's lecture is watercolors, which is earlier than oil paintings.
- Holden's lecture is sculptures, which is earlier than both Garcia's lecture and Jiang's lecture.
- Oil paintings and watercolors are both earlier than lithographs.
- This option satisfies all the constraints.

**Option C: Garcia: sculptures; Farley: watercolors; Holden: oil paintings; Jiang: lithographs**
- Farley's lecture is watercolors, which is not earlier than oil paintings.
- This option does not satisfy the second constraint.

**Option D: Holden: oil paintings; Jiang: watercolors; Farley: lithographs; Garcia: sculptures**
- Holden's lecture is oil paintings, which is not earlier than both Garcia's lecture and Jiang's lecture.
- This option does not satisfy the third constraint.

**Option E: Holden: sculptures; Farley: watercolors; Jiang: oil paintings; Garcia: oil paintings**
- Farley's lecture is watercolors, which is not earlier than oil paintings.
- This option does not satisfy the second constraint.

The only option that satisfies all the constraints is **Option B**. Therefore, the correct answer is:

\boxed{B}

question:
Four art historiansâ€”Farley, Garcia, Holden, and Jiangâ€”will give a series of four public lectures, each lecture on a different topicâ€”lithographs, oil paintings, sculptures, and watercolors. The lectures will be given one at a time, with each art historian giving a lecture on a different one of the topics. The schedule of the lectures is subject to the following constraints: The oil paintings lecture and the watercolors lecture must both be earlier than the lithographs lecture. Farley's lecture must be earlier than the oil paintings lecture. Holden's lecture must be earlier than both Garcia's lecture and Jiang's lecture.

Which one of the following CANNOT be true?
A) Farley gives the lithographs lecture.
B) Garcia gives the sculptures lecture.
C) Garcia gives the watercolors lecture.
D) Holden gives the oil paintings lecture.
E) Jiang gives the watercolors lecture.

question:
Four art historiansâ€”Farley, Garcia, Holden, and Jiangâ€”will give a series of four public lectures, each lecture on a different topicâ€”lithographs, oil paintings, sculptures, and watercolors. The lectures will be given one at a time, with each art historian giving a lecture on a different one of the topics. The schedule of the lectures is subject to the following constraints: The oil paintings lecture and the watercolors lecture must both be earlier than the lithographs lecture. Farley's lecture must be earlier than the oil paintings lecture. Holden's lecture must be earlier than both Garcia's lecture and Jiang's lecture.

If Garcia gives the sculptures lecture, which one of the following could be true?
A) The lithographs lecture is third.
B) The oil paintings lecture is third.
C) The sculptures lecture is first.
D) The sculptures lecture is second.
E) The watercolors lecture is second.
